title: Atheist Debates - Claims aren't evidence?

I've been called out, repeatedly, for my position that claims aren't evidence. So it's time to clear up what I mean, and why. 

In short, claims can contain evidence but they aren't evidence for what they're claiming. "I saw x happen" isn't evidence for x happening...because I could be lying or incorrect. It's the claim's consistency with the facts of reality that matter and it's the facts of reality, not the mere claim, that counts as evidence FOR the claim.

title: Atheist Debates - Arguing for vs against propositions
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

In order to clear up some confusion and work toward a couple of different video series, it's important to clarify the difference between arguing for and arguing against positions...and how to be clear that you're arguing against whether belief in X is reasonable (burden of proof met) or against whether X is true.

The distinctions between "I am not convinced" and "I am convinced of the opposite" as well as "I am convinced your reasoning is flawed" and "I am convinced your conclusion is false"...are both important clarifications when arguing.

One thing I didn't mention in the video is that they invited the writer/director of the film (which we argued about at AA) to their convention (as a special guest) and I was expressly told that it was about schmoozing someone 'in the industry' to promote their Batman and Jesus film...they care more about attention than truth, they care more about attention than being decent. Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Recorded in San Jose, in conjunction with The Village Forum and the Saratoga Federated Church - I sit down with mathematician Satyan Devadoss to discuss whether or not there's sufficient, good evidence to warrant belief in the Christian god.

title: Atheist Debates - Dillahunty vs Slick - Is Secular Humanism superior to Christianity?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Dallas, TX, October 2nd, 2016 - Matt Dillahunty and Matt Slick debate the question "Is Secular Humanism superior to Christianity?"

title: Atheist Debates - You're not an atheist, you're an agnostic
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Do the labels matter? What if they get in the way? Weren't we having a great issue-based conversation before you decided to change the topic to the labels?

title: Atheist Debates - What does atheism offer?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

I've frequently been asked "What does atheism have to offer?" - and it's come up so many times that it seemed like a good idea to offer a little more than the obvious answer.

title: Atheist Debates - Preparing for debates
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

A talk given to the Rationalists of East Tennessee, discussing how I view and prepare for debates, with tips for discussions that aren't formal debates.

title: Atheist Debates - Methodological Naturalism: A discussion with Blake Giunta
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Blake Giunta drove down from Dallas to engage in a debate review of our recent debate and this discussion about methodological naturalism...and what other methods one might use to reach a reasonable understanding of reality.

title: Atheist Debates - Debate review with Blake Giunta
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

As an experiment, I thought I'd try to do a debate review with my opponent from the debate in question. Blake and I have debated a few times and this is a partial review of our most recent debate (Did Jesus Rise From The Dead?) and a continuing discussion of that topic. The full debate is available here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3R4DYhpvNzc

I look forward to hearing whether people found this useful or if they prefer when I review debates on my own.

title: Atheist Debates - Did Jesus Rise From The Dead? Matt Dillahunty vs Blake Giunta
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Sponsored by thebibleandbeerconsortium.com, this debate was recorded August, 6th, 2016 in Dallas, Texas. The full debate is presented here (only intermissions and breaks have been excluded), without commentary.

A review of this debate will, most likely, be posted at a later date.

Enjoy!

title: Atheist Debates - Pre-debate interview with AronRa
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Just a few hours before Aron Ra's first live, public debate (with audience, moderator, etc.), I sat down to talk to him about the topic, the format, his preparation, what he anticipated and his general views on the both the specific subject and his take on debates.

Aron has posted the full video of the debate, as well as his post-debate thoughts at his channel: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xJqRK_9IyLE

title: Atheist Debates - Interview with Ozymandias Ramses II
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Ozy is a YouTube personality with a keen mind. His content specifically focuses on educating people about the finer points of philosophy, argumentation, reason and epistemology - with a specific focus on critical thinking and skepticism.

As an atheist, he frequently engages in online discussions about apologetic arguments that attempt to defend religious and superstitious ideas.

His efforts had a significant impact on me and I felt it'd be productive to share our most recent conversation, which included some thoughts related to The Atheist Debates project.

Enjoy. You can find Ozy's channel here: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCmthjMiFTIQnkGyZvfQKBdA

title: Atheist Debates - Finding out you were wrong
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

What does it feel like to find out you were wrong? Why is doubt discouraged? Why don't we encourage people for changing their mind for good reasons?

During my visit to the Dallas Fellowship of Freethought, I discuss this, and more.

title: Atheist Debates - Argument from Contingency
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

In the realm of cosmological arguments, arguments from contingency are less typical than first-cause arguments or the Kalam cosmological argument, but it plays to the heart of our curiosity over why there is something instead of nothing.

title: Atheist Debates - Conversation with the Apologetics Academy
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

This 3+ hour discussion was an online conversation with members and guests of The Apologetics Academy. It's presented here, in full, without additional commentary. As one of the goals of the Atheist Debates project is to give my thoughts and recommendations on how to engage with apologists, this video serves as an example of my thoughts - in action - on that topic.

Specific questions related to this video will be addressed in future uploads.

title: Atheist Debates - Debating nonchristian religions
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Recorded at CFI, Pittsburgh, this video looks at whether one needs to become an expert in any (or all) religions in order to engage in discussions about them...and challenges the assumptions that atheists are focused solely on Christianity by noting that the bulk of the classical arguments for a god apply to many different religions.

title: Atheist Debates - Do they really believe that?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Recorded at CFI headquarters in Amherst, NY, this talk focuses on and argues against the frequent claim that religious folks really don't believe what they claim to believe. In some cases, they do (or might) in others they may 'believe in belief'...so do they really believe? Did I?

title: Atheist Debates - Spiritual but not Religious
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

This talk, delivered in Regina, SK, Canada takes a look at those who label themselves 'spiritual but not religious'.

title: Atheist Debates - Is Anything really possible?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Anything is possible. That's what we frequently hear, but is it actually true? It seems that some theists attempt to leverage this platitude as a foundation to shift the burden of proof and build "not impossible" into "possible" and extend it further to "true and worth betting my life on"...with little more than wishes and fallacies to support this chain.

title: Atheist Debates - Is 3 really a magic number?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Biblical numerology, gammatria, Bible codes and other attempts to identify mystical patterns and messages in ancient texts and in the fabric of reality...are we actually finding something real, or just what we're looking for?

title: Atheist Debates - Orlando Q&A
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

A live Q&A session in Orlando Florida.

NOTE: There was an audio interference problem. I've used a couple of filters to make the static less loud and annoying - this makes the conversation difficult to hear. 

I've purchased a Zoom H6 recorder to help make sure this problem doesn't occur in the future. Any audiophiles who think they can better fix the problem are free to email.

title: Atheist Debates - A discussion about Hell...
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

What is hell? Is it a literal place of torture and torment? Is it separation from a god? Is it annihilation? Is there anything real behind the threats? Which religion's hell should we avoid? What is this concept doing to people?

This talk was delivered to the UU Humanists of Tampa Florida in April, 2016.

title: Atheist Debates - Thinking about logical fallacies
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

While we may go through specific, common fallacies and how to spot them in future videos, this video offers a quick review of validity and soundness along with some thoughts on the sort of heuristic processes our brains might use when evaluating claims. I've included some tips on how to practice analyzing arguments - because you're not going to be an expert overnight!

title: Atheist Debates - Professing Atheist?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

From time to time we'll see and hear atheists referred to as "professed atheist", "self-professed atheist" and "professing atheist". What does this mean? Where does it come from? Is it just a claim that we're lying?

Or does it tell us far more about the person using the label than the person the label is applied to?

title: Atheist Debates - Borrowing from the Christian worldview
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

In debates that focus on the foundations of reason and morality, we've often heard the accusation that atheists are just borrowing from the Christian worldview. What does that really mean?...

title: Atheist Debates - Debate review: Does God Exist? with Jay Lucas Part 3
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

In April of 2012, I debated Jay Lucas on the topic, "Does God Exist?"

The entire debate can be viewed here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UV1FC7exLKA

This video is part of a series that provides additional commentary, corrections and clarifications of the topic discussed. Over the course of this series, we'll look at mistakes that were made by all parties in the hope that others can avoid those mistakes.

This is Part 3 and covers the cross-examination and closing.

title: Atheist Debates - Minimal facts apologetics approach
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

The "Minimal Facts" approach isn't a method designed to find the truth, it's a method designed to bolster confidence in the proposed (read: preferred) explanation.

title: Atheist Debates - Debate review: Does God Exist? with Jay Lucas Part 2
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

In April of 2012, I debated Jay Lucas on the topic, "Does God Exist?"

The entire debate can be viewed here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UV1FC7exLKA

This video is part of a series that provides additional commentary, corrections and clarifications of the topic discussed. Over the course of this series, we'll look at mistakes that were made by all parties in the hope that others can avoid those mistakes.

This is Part 2 and covers the rebuttals/second statements. In the 3rd video, we'll cover the remainder of the debate as well as circumstances and topics surrounding this debate.

title: Atheist Debates - Abraham and Isaac
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

The three Abrahamic religions (Judaism, Islam and Christianity) share a foundation that rests, in part, on the story of Abraham and Isaac (or, Ishmael, in the case of Islam). This story has strangely been preached as a lovely story of obedience and the foundation of a covenant with God...but what does the story really tell us?

title: Atheist Debates - The Exodus
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

The story of the Exodus isn't merely missing supporting evidence, it's wholly unbelievable. The presentation of the characters and their actions isn't consistent with a group of people who witnessed miraculous events - and the actions of the God of this story represent an individual as confused, irrational and unbelievable as the people writing the story.

title: Atheist Debates - Liar, Lunatic or Lord?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

C.S. Lewis popularized the trilemma of "liar, lunatic or lord" and Josh McDowell, and others, ran with that in order to firm up a foundation that may seek to exclude other options.

Links:
http://infidels.org/library/modern/jeff_lowder/jury/

title: Atheist Debates - Debate review: Does God Exist? with Jay Lucas Part 1
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

In April of 2012, I debated Jay Lucas on the topic, "Does God Exist?"

The entire debate can be viewed here:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UV1FC7exLKA

This video is part of a series that provides additional commentary, corrections and clarifications of the topic discussed. Over the course of this series, we'll look at mistakes that were made by all parties in the hope that others can avoid those mistakes.

This is Part 1 and covers the opening remarks. As we continue discussing this debate, we'll also cover the remainder of the debate as well as circumstances and topics surrounding this debate.

title: Atheist Debates - Engage or Enrage?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

A discussion about goals, tactics and style when having conversations with theists. This conversation took place using Blab (beta) and involved Anthony Magnabosco, Joshua Kelly, Peter Boghossian and Matt Dillahunty

title: Atheist Debates - Burden of proof
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

There seems to be a lot of confusion around  the burden of proof with respect to default positions and with respect to what it is - and isn't. Here's a quick "propositional logic 101" look at the burden of proof.

title: Atheist Debates - Who are you to question God?
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

In discussions about the character and actions ascribed to a god, we're asked to evaluate and reach a conclusion - often encouraged to "choose god". Why then, when we offer an honest evaluation, do we sometimes hear, "Who are you to question God?"

title: Atheist Debates - Debate: Does the Soul Exist? Eric Hernandez vs Matt Dillahunty
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Does the soul exist? Eric Hernandez vs Matt Dillahunty

Filmed at First Evangelical Lutheran Church in Houston, TX.

title: Atheist Debates - Interview: Dan Barker
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Dan Barker is co-president of the Freedom From Religion Foundation (ffrf.org). He famously journeyed from preacher to atheist and has been in more than 120 formal public debates, making him a great resource for those interested in debating.

Filmed at the FreeFLO.org humanist convention in November, 2015.

title: Atheist Debates - Debate: Does God Exist? Matt Dillahunty vs John Ferrer
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Does God Exist? A debate between Matt Dillahunty and John Ferrer.

Filmed in Clarksville, Tennesee November 4th, 2015.

title: Atheist Debates: The Bible, Part 1 - The Sermon on the Mount
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

The first  in a series of videos covering different Biblical topics. In 2007 I finished a verse-by-verse deconstruction of the Sermon on the Mount (hosted at wiki.ironchariots.org). This video covers most of the content in that article with a few additional remarks.

You don't have to know a lot about the Bible to have a conversation about it, because you're free to ask questions of the person advocating for it. But if you're going to have a discussion about whether or not their doctrine makes sense, it's good to have a basic grounding in the topic.

Hopefully, this video will provide food for thought and some objections and concerns that will allow more productive conversations, exposing the weaknesses of appeals to scripture.

title: Atheist Debates - Debate: Does God Exist? (Second debate) with Blake Giunta
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Does God Exist? - A second debate on this topic, between Matt Dillahunty and Blake Giunta.

Filmed in San Diego, California on October 13th, 2015.

title: Atheist Debates - Debate: Does science move us toward or away from God? With Jon Morrison
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Does science move us toward or away from God? A debate between Matt Dillahunty and Jon Morrison.

Filmed in Red Deer, AB, October 17th, 2015. Sponsored by Alberta Secular Conference, Society of Edmonton Atheists and Living Stones Church.

title: Atheist Debates - Divine Hiddenness
description: A lecture at Baylor University on why I prefer the problem of Divine Hiddenness to the Problem of Evil.

title: Atheist Debates - Interview: Muhammad Syed
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Muhammad Syed, Co-Founder and President of Ex-Muslims of North America sits down to talk about his views about Islam and debating with Muslims.

title: Atheist Debates - The Problem of Evil
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

While the Problem of Evil has been a long-standing favorite argument against many different god models, I don't find it particularly compelling and am very particular about when and how I use it.

In this video, I'll talk about why that's the case...and it's all preparation for an argument that I personally view as a much more effective and powerful argument.

title: JT Eberhard is NOT ready for a debate at Apostacon
description: Visit apostacon.org for tickets and information. The ass-whoopin' commences on Sunday afternoon...and he hasn't got a prayer.

title: Atheist Debates - Religion and Fear
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Religions exploit our existing fears and sometimes manufacture fears that are exploited. Can this continue? Are we doomed to be fearful forever?

As we learn more about the world, it seems that religions grasp on the emotional anxieties of the world may be destined to fail.

title: Atheist Debates: But that's the Old Testament!
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

When pointing out potential problems with the Bible, one of the more common responses is, "But that's the OLD Testament". So, what does this mean? What exactly are they saying? Do they really know that they're admitting a problem and then trying to solve it...and failing?

title: Atheist Debates - Appeals to Personal Experience
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

You're more likely to hear about people's personal experience with religion in a testimonial form than any of the standard arguments for the existence of God.

In this live presentation from Gateway To Reason, I talk about the problem with appealing to personal experience and how to think about those appeals when you're talking to believers.

And, there's a bonus magic trick.

title: Atheist Debates - Interview: Dr. Jerry Coyne
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Dr. Jerry Coyne is a professor of biology at the University of Chicago. He holds a Ph.D. from Harvard and is the author of both "Why Evolution Is True" and "Faith vs. Fact". 

You can visit his blog and find more information about him here:
https://whyevolutionistrue.wordpress.com/

title: Atheist Debates - Debate: Does God Exist? with Blake Giunta
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Does God Exist? A debate between Matt Dillahunty and Blake Giunta.

Part 1 - The Debate.
Part 2 - Audience Q&A: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Lc9SRKRYCo

You can find another video of this debate, in which Blake's slides are more clearly visible, here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ea_p5eQE-iM&feature=youtu.be

title: Atheist Debates - Debate Q&A: Does God Exist? with Blake Giunta
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Does God Exist? A debate between Matt Dillahunty and Blake Giunta.

Part 1 - The Debate: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0_516npqF18
Part 2 - Audience Q&A

title: Atheist Debates - A Better Life, with Chris Johnson
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

A discussion with Chris Johnson about the book and film "A Better Life"... a project covering 100 atheists talking about joy and meaning in a world without god.

For a list of scheduled screenings, information on how to watch the film online or to purchase the book or film, visit:

www.theatheistbook.com.

title: Atheist Debates - The Bible Doesn't Say That!
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

When addressing various doctrinal positions or claims associated with the Bible, some atheists over-reach...exaggerating or misrepresenting what the text says or which interpretation of that text is most likely accurate or common...and so do Christians.

How do we address claims in the Bible when it's all a matter of interpretation and context?

title: Atheist Debates - Interview: Dr. Robert M. Price
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Dr. Robert Price teaches philosophy and religion at the Johnnie Colemon Theological Seminary. He has a PhD in Systematic Theology and a second PhD in the New Testament. A published author and recognized expert in the history of Christianity, biblical criticism, and theology, Dr. Price has also written books on the historicity of Jesus and the various Christ myth theories.

He has served as a fellow of the Jesus Seminar, the former editor of the Journal of Higher Criticism, a fellow of the Center For Inquiry's Committee on the Scientific examination of Religion and the advisory board of the Secular Student Alliance.

He graciously agreed to sit down with us to discuss the historicity of Jesus and how or if this topic has relevance in debates and discussions with Christians.

title: Atheist Debates - Science and intellect are your gods!
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

From time to time atheists are told that they've turned science, intellect and similar things into their "god" or their "religion". This non-argument is a mix of insult (though it may insult their god and religion more), tu quoque fallacy and... just a touch of truth, but a truth that betrays a larger problem with their view.

This may be one of the biggest and most damning deepities we've heard.

title: Atheist Debates - Can Science Disprove God(s)?
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

An e-mail from a new debater prompts me to address this question, why it's probably not a good idea to defend the affirmative and what I think you ought to do if you find yourself in that position.

title: Atheist Debates - Interview: AC Grayling, DPhil
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Professor, A.C. Grayling, DPhil (Oxon) is the author of more than 30 books on Philosophy, Humanism and related topics. In 2011 he founded and became the first Master of the New College of the Humanities in London.

In addition to his academic career, he also serves as a Vice President of the British Humanist Association and sits on the board of several philosophical and humanist organizations.

I was fortunate to be speaking at QEDcon.org in Manchester along with Professor Grayling and he graciously agreed to sit down for this interview about philosophy, religion, debates and humanism.

title: Unholy Trinity Down Under - Sydney Q&A
description:
In March of 2015, the Atheist Foundation of Australia hosted atheist activists Matt Dillahunty, Aron Ra and Seth Andrews (under the tongue-in-cheek tour title, "The Unholy Trinity Down Under").

The speakers' presentations from Sydney, Brisbane and Melbourne are posted on AFA's tour website: http://www.unholytrinitydownunder.com

Special thanks to the AFA:  http://atheistfoundation.org.au

title: Matt Dillahunty - Unholy Trinity Down Under: "Why Won't You Love Me?" (Version 2)
description:
In March of 2015, the Atheist Foundation of Australia hosted atheist activists Matt Dillahunty, Aron Ra and Seth Andrews (under the tongue-in-cheek tour title, "The Unholy Trinity Down Under").

The speakers' presentations from Sydney, Brisbane and Melbourne are posted on AFA's tour website: http://www.unholytrinitydownunder.com

Special thanks to the AFA:  http://atheistfoundation.org.au

title: Matt Dillahunty - Unholy Trinity Down Under: "Why Won't You Love Me?" (Version 1)
description:
In March of 2015, the Atheist Foundation of Australia hosted atheist activists Matt Dillahunty, Aron Ra and Seth Andrews (under the tongue-in-cheek tour title, "The Unholy Trinity Down Under").

The speakers' presentations from Sydney, Brisbane and Melbourne are posted on AFA's tour website: http://www.unholytrinitydownunder.com

Special thanks to the AFA:  http://atheistfoundation.org.au

title: Atheist Debates - Yall just want to sin
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

Some apologists seek to avoid defending their position or addressing the merits of atheists' positions by simply suggesting that our reasons for disbelief are emotional and driven by a desire to 'sin' rather than intellectual and driven by a concern for the truth.

"Y'all just want to sin." Takes a look at example or two and offers my thoughts (new and old) on how to address this dodgy tactic.

title: Atheist Debates - "Does it Satisfy"
description:
While in Melbourne, Australia, I had the opportunity to engage in a conversation with an evangelical pastor who was a former Atheist. We each discuss why we hold our current positions as well as discussing various worldview issues.

The original topic, "Does it satisfy" was meant to compare a Christian world view with an atheistic world view to see which one was more satisfying. While I'm far more concerned with which truth than satisfaction, I tried to point out that while I may not be primarily concerned with which is satisfying, I do find rational atheism to be far more satisfying.

The event was arranged by the City Bible Forum in Melbourne, Australia.

title: Atheist Debates - Interview: Anthony Pinn, PhD
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

Dr. Anthony Pinn is a prolific author and the Agnes Cullen Arnold Professor of Humanities and Professor of Religious Studies at Rice University in Houston, TX.

A former child preacher, Dr. Pinn abandoned his former religious beliefs and has spent many years teaching and studying issues surrounding Black humanism, religion and related topics.

(My audio is a little low through this, but it's most important that we get to hear Dr. Pinn speak).

title: Atheist Debates - Supernatural Causation
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

Many of the claims made by apologists hinge on the ability to confirm the existence of the supernatural and that the supernatural could serve as a cause for various effects. Is there any way to do this? Aren't many theists claiming to be little God-detectors?

title: Atheist Debates - Debate Tips and thoughts
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

In response to e-mails requesting general tips and thoughts on debates, I've put together a partial list of things to think about when you're engaging in discussions and debates. Why are you doing this? What's your motivation? How do you avoid mistakes? What should you avoid doing? How do you reach an audience?

title: Atheist Debates - Slavery and bad apologetics...
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

In response to another YouTube channel that challenged me to 'debate' the topic of slavery in the Bible, we take a look at what the Bible says about slavery, by actually reading the passages. (Something that not enough believers actually bother to do).

The individual I'm responding to doesn't seem to represent any typical Christian view. Some of his arguments are typical while others are far from typical. The takeaway is that it's probably not going to be worthwhile to address fringe positions - but knowing that they're out there will help you recognize when you might be wasting your time.

title: Atheist Debates - Interview: AronRa
description:
Part of the Atheist Debates Patreon project: http://www.patreon.com/AtheistDebates

AronRa is the Texas State director for American Atheists as well as an activist and promoter of science education.

http://www.aronra.com

title: Atheist Debates - Morality
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

The topic that just keeps coming up...so let's take a look at morality.

Filmed on location at: Pedernales Falls State Park.

title: Atheist Debates - Patterns of Evidence: Exodus - An Assessment
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

A very old issue (dating the Biblical exodus) is addressed in a new documentary called "Patterns of Evidence: Exodus". I take a cursory look at the film and offer my thoughts on what we do and don't know about the exodus.

title: Atheist Debates - Prophecy Part 1
description:
From the Atheist Debates Patreon project (http://tinyurl.com/prnfbx5):

Appeals to prophecy serve as a sort of confidence game in support of other religious claims. Exploiting our desires, fears, ignorance, innumeracy and our general need to find trusted sources, they attempt to build our confidence in the source of prophecies...a feat that they can't actually accomplish.

In part 1, we explain this problem and note why we really don't need a part 2 in this series (though we'll continue the series to examine claims of fulfilled prophecy, as well.
